  "slug": "beef-and-barley-stew",
  "title": "Beef and Barley Stew",
  "subtitle": "Slow-cooked beef shin with pearl barley and root vegetables in a thick, hearty broth",
  "excerpt": "Beef and barley stew is a hob or oven braise of beef shin with pearl barley and root vegetables. The barley thickens the stock naturally as it cooks and adds a soft, nutty grain to each bowlful. It takes 2.5 hours and produces a stew that is richer and more filling than any recipe with fewer ingredients deserves to be.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Traditional British and Scottish. F. Marian McNeill, The Scots Kitchen (1929): Scotch broth with barley and lamb. Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136: barley broth. British farmhouse cooking tradition.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The key to this stew is ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "beef shin",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr55e50001w4v4qkvqotst"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ": its high collagen content gives the broth a body that no amount of stock cube can replicate. Braising steak or beef chuck will produce a good stew, but the texture of the finished liquid with shin is noticeably richer.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "pearl barley",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr55d70000w4v4zkhm5178"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " after 90 minutes of cooking, not at the start. Added too early, it absorbs too much liquid and the stew becomes claggy. Added at the right time, it swells to a soft, nutty grain and thickens the broth just enough.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
