      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown the beef and build the base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{olive-oil}} of olive oil",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " in a large casserole over high heat. Season the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{beef-shin}} of beef shin",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and dust with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{plain-flour}} of flour",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Brown in batches for 3-4 minutes per side until deeply coloured. Remove and set aside. Reduce heat to medium. Add the onion, carrot, and celery and cook for 8 minutes. Add garlic, ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{bay-leaves}} of bay",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{thyme}} of thyme",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Return the beef. Add ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-beef}} of beef stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Bring to a simmer, cover, and cook on the lowest hob heat (or in a 160°C oven) for 90 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the barley and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Stir in the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{pearl-barley}} of pearl barley",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Check the liquid level; add a splash of water or stock if the pot is looking dry. Replace the lid and cook for a further 40-50 minutes until the beef is completely tender and the barley is soft. Season with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Remove the thyme sprigs and bay leaves. Serve with flat-leaf parsley if using.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Add hot stock or water in small amounts to reach the consistency you want. Barley keeps absorbing liquid; serve the stew as soon as it is ready.",
              "cause": "Barley added too early, or pot was left on too high a heat",
              "symptom": "Stew is too thick and the barley has absorbed all the stock"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Reduce the heat to the barest simmer. Beef shin requires low, steady heat; boiling makes it tough rather than tender.",
              "cause": "The heat was too high, causing the muscle fibres to tighten rather than relax",
              "symptom": "Beef is tough after 2.5 hours"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Remove the lid and simmer uncovered for 15-20 minutes to reduce. If still thin, the beef may not have been high enough in collagen; next time use more shin rather than chuck.",
              "cause": "Too much stock for the volume of collagen in the meat",
              "symptom": "Broth is thin and lacks body"
            },
            {
              "fix": "For a tidier result, add fresh diced carrot and celery at the same time as the barley so they cook for only 40 minutes.",
              "cause": "Added at the start and cooked for too long",
              "symptom": "Vegetables are mushy"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Beef and barley stew sits alongside Scotch broth as one of the defining British grain-thickened soups. The Scottish version traditionally uses lamb or mutton with barley, leek, and turnip; the English version more often uses beef and is served as a thick stew rather than a broth. Both are made to feed a large group from inexpensive cuts and last well in the refrigerator.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
